title: For Sale:  How To Spot a SCAM / FRAUD Post
postcontent:
Most of the time, using a very small amount of common sense, you should be able to spot a SCAM / FRAUD listing almost the moment you click on it.

Take, for example, the listing just below for a "SPRINGFIELD ARMORY M1A STANDARD 308 NO RESERVE 2 MAGAZINES INCLUDED - ONE 10 ROUND AND ONE 20"

Gee... what do we have here:
http://www.gunbroker.com/Auction/ViewItem.aspx?Item=326884725

It has all of the hallmarks of a SCAM listing -- notice it has "NO RESERVE" in the title, meaning this was posted by a LAZY scammer that just cut-and-pasted the listing from a site like Gunbroker, etc. The scammer doesn't bother to post an actual LOCATION for the gun anywhere, just "Alabama". I'll bet, if contacted, he'll claim the gun is actually in some far-off location just waiting to be shipped to the FFL of your choice -- after payment, of course. Also, he doesn't include any contact info or even a first name. He does say anything about anything. Also, check the "Listings by this user" feature to see if he's trolling with more scams and FLAG THEM ALL.

So... FLAG ANY LISTING that does not provide at least SOME of the following:

(1)  A real location where the item is located. 
(2)  Information other than Cut-and-Paste specs, etc.
(3)  A person's first name and/or contact info.

Or posts that have dead-giveaway text like "NO RESERVE", etc.

Yes, some legitimate posts will be flagged, but they can re-post afterward with more substantive, less questionable information afterward. This will help others and weed out on forum noise that is at a fevered pitch right now.

Anyway, take it FWIW. Just trying to help.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Desktop Computer (and a bunch of other computer-related stuff)
postcontent:
I’ve got some computers (and other office stuff) to trade.  I’ve been an IT Consultant for many years, with a side project of making artwork out of old computer parts in my spare time.  This used to be a good accompaniment back in the day – a part or two would go out, I’d replace the bad, and then keep the bad piece to make a sculpture or wall hanging or something.  Anymore, though, computers hold up a lot better so I’m not getting nearly as much stuff as I used to.

I’m working with a company right now to replace some of their aging technology.  Most of the computers I will have are going to be Dell desktops of moderate performance – if you’re looking for a top-of-the-line gaming system or something, I’m not going to have anything for you.  If, though, you’re looking for something for the kids to tinker with so they stay off your computer, something for just web browsing, that sort of thing, keep reading!

The specific computer in this posting is a Dimension 2400.  It has a Pentium 4 Processor, rated at 3.06ghz, with 2gb of RAM and a 40gb Hard Drive.  The hard drive has been wiped and I installed linux on the computer – the case does have a sticker with a key for Windows XP, so if you would rather have that installed you can get a disk and do so.  

I’d value this computer at about $20, out the door, with a mouse, keyboard and power cable.  If you need a monitor, we can talk – I have a few that I can offer.

Other stuff to trade – I have a Canon PC420 Copier, a Photosmart A646 Photo Printer, a Laserjet 3015 All-In-One unit, several computer cases of different sizes and shapes, computer power supplies, keyboards, mice, etc – if you’re looking for something that came out of an office, shoot me a message and maybe I can help you out!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Can someone explain striker fire action?
postcontent:
A previous post got me thinking about this again.
Ok, in striker fire, so the firing pin is one piece. Big deal?

Why is a gun listed with an "Action: Striker fire" The firing pin is not an action, its a component of the gun. Action is how the gun operates. How does a striker fire gun operate? Striker fire is not an answer to that question.

This doesnt explain if it is a single action, double action only, or single/double action.

postcontent:
Mossberg 715T (tactical) .22 LR AR15 style rifle, fixed stock, 25 rd magazine, NIB

All federal and state laws apply. Buyer must complete ATF form 4473 and pass a standard background check in person. Ohio sales tax will be collected from Ohio buyer. Please be sure the information on your driver's license is correct so that we can accept that for required identification purposes. 3.5% credit card processing fees apply; cash and check price is what is listed. We will complete out of state sales by transferring the gun to your local FFL holder who will then complete the paperwork and background check. Shipping is normally $30, which covers packaging, shipping costs, tracking numbers, and insurance to the lower 48 states. Know your state gun laws before buying as there are no returns on this item. If there is a manufacturing defect, the repair will be handled by the manufacturer's warranty or through our distributor's warranty. This listing will be deleted if the gun is sold.

Please contact David Greer with Free Republic Firearms at REDACTED or by phone at REDACTED with any questions. To get updates of our new arrivals, "like" our facebook page, and visit www.freerepublicfirearms.com for more information. If you contact us via email, please include your name and phone number to eliminate spammers and to ensure we can contact you. Lately we have been having problems with messages from hidden email addresses that are sent through gun listing/auction sites. The emails are being returned as undeliverable, so if we don't respond to your email, please make sure we have another way to contact you.

We will consider firearms trades, but we cannot give a value on a gun unless we see it in person. Please realize will cannot pay full retail for your firearm. We are a business, and there has to be room for us to make a small amount when we resell the firearm.

To all the spammers and criminals that can't legally buy guns, don't contact us asking to meet in a parking lot to complete a cash sale, or to trade a stolen laptop or other electronics for our guns. You shouldn't have guns, and we're definitely not going to help you get one.

To those who are under the legal age to buy firearms or handguns, we understand your desire to have a gun, but we will not break the law to sell you one, so please don't ask. We believe that if an 18 year old is old enough to fight for our country in the armed forces, they should be able to buy a gun. But until a little common sense is used in Washington DC, we cannot sell handguns to anyone under 21, and long guns to anyone under 18.
